From: Xin Xiong <xiongx18@fudan.edu.cn>
Date: Sun, 24 Jul 2022 17:55:58 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] xfrm: fix refcount leak in __xfrm_policy_check()
Git-commit: 9c9cb23e00ddf45679b21b4dacc11d1ae7961ebe
Patch-mainline: v6.0-rc3
References: CVE-2022-50007 bsc#1245016

The issue happens on an error path in __xfrm_policy_check(). When the
fetching process of the object `pols[1]` fails, the function simply
returns 0, forgetting to decrement the reference count of `pols[0]`,
which is incremented earlier by either xfrm_sk_policy_lookup() or
xfrm_policy_lookup(). This may result in memory leaks.

Fix it by decreasing the reference count of `pols[0]` in that path.

Fixes: 134b0fc544ba ("IPsec: propagate security module errors up from flow_cache_lookup")
Signed-off-by: Xin Xiong <xiongx18@fudan.edu.cn>
Signed-off-by: Xin Tan <tanxin.ctf@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Steffen Klassert <steffen.klassert@secunet.com>
Signed-off-by: David Sterba <dsterba@suse.com>
---
 net/xfrm/xfrm_policy.c |    1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

--- a/net/xfrm/xfrm_policy.c
+++ b/net/xfrm/xfrm_policy.c
@@ -2542,6 +2542,7 @@ int __xfrm_policy_check(struct sock *sk,
 		if (pols[1]) {
 			if (IS_ERR(pols[1])) {
 				XFRM_INC_STATS(net, LINUX_MIB_XFRMINPOLERROR);
+				xfrm_pol_put(pols[0]);
 				return 0;
 			}
 			pols[1]->curlft.use_time = get_seconds();
